          "title": "A theology of long obedience under judgment",
          "body": "Read whole, Jeremiah 29 articulates a theology of *long obedience in the same direction*, to borrow Peterson's phrase. Three convictions hold it together: (1) **God's sovereignty over both judgment and restoration** — He sent them to Babylon (v.4) and He will gather them back (v.14). Babylon is not outside His jurisdiction. (2) **Faithful presence in the place of exile** — settling, marrying, building, seeking the city's welfare. The exile is not a parenthesis in life; it IS life, for a generation. (3) **Discernment between true and false prophetic words** — both spoken in the same name, distinguished only by divine commission and verified by historical fulfillment. The chapter teaches the people of God how to live when the time God has appointed exceeds the time His people would prefer."
